04310nam a22006855i 9780292745124DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212000txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927451247 a10.7560/7710242doi  a(DE-B1597)586568  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF394.S29bM57 2000 7aSOC0080002bisacsh04a324/.089/687207643512211 aRosales, Rodolfo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Illusion of Inclusion :bThe Untold Political Story of San Antonio /cRodolfo Rosales. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 / Introduction -- t2 / Posing the Correct Questions -- tPart One. The Partisan Era -- t3 / The Shaping of a Political Agenda and Its Consequences -- t4 / Coalition Politics: Trench Political Warfare -- tPart Two. A Period of Transition -- t5 / The Changing of the Guard -- t6 / The Transitional Period -- tPart Three. Political Pluralism and Its Consequences -- t7 / Style and Strategy in San Antonio Politics -- t8 / The Cultural Is Political; the Political Is Cultural -- t9 / The Question of Inclusion: A Final Note -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTo many observers, the 1981 election of Henry Cisneros as mayor of San Antonio, Texas, represented the culminating victory in the Chicano community's decades-long struggle for inclusion in the city's political life. Yet, nearly twenty years later, inclusion is still largely an illusion for many working-class and poor Chicanas and Chicanos, since business interests continue to set the city's political and economic priorities. In this book, Rodolfo Rosales offers the first in-depth history of the Chicano community's struggle for inclusion in the political life of San Antonio during the years 1951 to 1991, drawn from interviews with key participants as well as archival research. He focuses on the political and organizational activities of the Chicano middle class in the context of post-World War II municipal reform and how it led ultimately to independent political representation for the Chicano community. Of special interest is his extended discussion of the role of Chicana middle-class women as they gained greater political visibility in the 1980s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMexican Americans -- Texas -- San Antonio -- Politics and government -- 20th century. 0aMexican AmericanszTexaszSan AntonioxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aMiddle class -- Political activity -- Texas -- San Antonio -- History -- 20th century. 0aMiddle classxPolitical activityzTexaszSan AntonioxHistoryy20th century. 0aSan Antonio (Tex.) -- Ethnic relations. 0aSan Antonio (Tex.) -- Politics and government -- 20th century. 0aSan Antonio (Tex.) -- Social conditions -- 20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/77102440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292745124423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292745124/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK